💫FREE Visual Arts idea!💫
°
Looking for a Valentine Art idea? This one is sure to capture the hearts of your students while at the same time teaching them about line, value, colour, form and texture!
°

Drop any emoji below 🖤 or use the link in my BIO to grab the heart template for this lesson for FREE💫
°
Materials Needed:
💕 White Paper (I used cardstock)
💕 Markers or watercolour paint 
💕 Washi Tape
💕 Hearts
💕 Any colour paper for hearts (I used black cardstock)
°
Instructions:
1. Using washi tape create a boarder and divide the page into quarters
2. Draw an "x" in quadrant 2 and 4. Draw an 'o' in quadrant 1 and 3.
3. Using colours or watercolour paint,  begin drawing 'x' and 'o' layers right up to the boarder.
4. Remove washi tape
5. Using the heart template trace or cut out 10 coloured hearts. 
6. Glue one heart flat in the center of the page.
7. Fold the remaining 9 hearts in half.
8. Glue one side of the folded heart down to the flat heart and do the same with the next heart.
9. Continue to do this until all hearts have been used. 
10. Glue the last two hearts together to create a 3D heart 💕

Podcasts all about L-O-V-E and we're ready to listen ❤️
°
Read on to see how I will be implementing these 5 podcast episodes on Valentine's Day!
°
1️⃣Brainstorm (Whole Class) 
My class is obsessed with podcasts, but have they really thought about the components of a good podcast? We will begin by brainstorming ideas on what components are included in a podcast and record these ideas on chart paper. 

2️⃣ Groups 
Next, I will divide my students in 5 groups of 3-4 students (I like 3 students per group for optimal learning). Each group will receive a QR code which will have the link to a podcast on the theme of L-O-V-E and a podcast booklet.  All groups will be assigned a different podcast. 

Prior to listening to the podcast, we will review the podcast booklet and rubric to ensure students have a clear understanding along with group expectations. 

3️⃣ Listen 
Let the fun begin!  First, I will instruct students to complete the first two columns of the KWL chart (in booklet) then to listen to the podcast in it’s entirety and discuss as a group. Afterwards, students will listen to the podcast a second time and begin completing the work independently in their podcast booklet. 

 4️⃣ Group Talk 
Students can work collaboratively in their groups to discuss their podcast and I will circulate and provide prompts to help generate discussion.

5️⃣ Whole Class
I plan on extending this further and have groups share with the class what their podcast is about, what was surprising and what they learned. We will revisit our brainstorming question on the components of a podcast and discuss any additional components that we may have missed. 

WHY I LOVE USING PODCASTS? 
✔️They are free 
✔️I’m able to connect the whole class together vs. finding the right fit book for book clubs 
✔️Encourages my reluctant readers to literacy 
✔️Topics are often of high interest to intermediate students 
✔️There are hooked on exploring other audio and even audiobooks.  This opens up a whole new world for them and I’m all for it. 🖤✌️

Sharing a Few Practices in my Classroom:
°
1. Feedback Slips: Students can often get really caught up in their grades. while grades are a type of feedback, students don’t often use them as such. By holding off on grades and providing these feedback slips, it can help students to better focus on the descriptive feedback that you give and focus on ways to improve their work. 

👉If you subscribe to my email list you can find these feedback slips for reading. writing and math in my freebie library.
 °
2. Self-Assessment Bin: Prior to students turning in their work, they highlight their name with a colour to indicate their level of understanding. This provides feedback for myself to see how students view their own work as they progress to being an expert and being able to teach the concept to a peer in the classroom.  More importantly, it helps students to take ownership of their own learning, meet learning goals, become reflective students on how they feel about learning certain concepts and not forget to put their name on their work 🙃
°
3. Class slips: I use class slips to keep track of just about everything in my classroom but I absolutely love them for a quick reference on student assessment for a specific task.  By recording their assessment on these slips I am able to have a quick overall reference on the needs in my classroom and those who understood the task at hand.

We Are Many, We Are One.
🦋
This week we celebrate the gift of Catholic Education. During this week, students, teachers and families come together to reflect on the values and teachings of Catholic faith, and to recognize the important role that Catholic schools play in the development of well-rounded individuals. 
🦋
Our theme this year is 'We Are Many, We Are One' and this bulletin board is a reflection of the vibrant and inclusive community that makes Catholic Education so special.  Each butterfly is diverse (many) and joins our white butterflies in unity to signify how we are one in our faith. Students in our school created their unique butterfly and wrote what Catholic Education means to them.

✏️🎅Started off the holiday season exploring a variety of drawing styles!
°
1.Began by exploring the different styles of drawing and their connection to the elements of art. The styles are (Drip, glitch, pixel, xray, blur and glow). Look at examples of the different styles  in artworks. For example, Jen stark is known for her Drip artwork. 
°
2. Model the different styles using your own holiday drawing (trace it onto paper) and look at how each style creates a visual effect. There are lots of videos on YouTube on the different styles and many students are already familiar with them. 
°
3.Students began to create their own first by drawing their picture, dividing the page into quarters and drawing/colouring a style of their choice in each of the quarters. 
°
4. Students reflect on their artwork. What worked? What they found challenging? Changes they would make? Etc...
°

💫Drop a 🖤 below to grab this FREE heart template + bulletin board letters that will capture the hearts of your students while at the same time teaching them about line, value, colour, form and texture!
°
°
Materials Needed:
💕 White Paper (I used @astrobrights cardstock)
💕 Markers or watercolour paint 
💕 Washi Tape
💕 Hearts
💕 Any colour paper for hearts (I used black @astrobrights cardstock)
°
Instructions:
1. Using washi tape create a boarder and divide the page into quarters
2. Draw an "x" in quadrant 2 and 4. Draw an 'o' in quadrant 1 and 3.
3. Using colours or watercolour paint,  begin drawing 'x' and 'o' layers right up to the boarder.
4. Remove washi tape
5. Using the heart template trace or cut out 10 coloured hearts. 
6. Glue one heart flat in the center of the page.
7. Fold the remaining 9 hearts in half.
8. Glue one side of the folded heart down to the flat heart and do the same with the next heart.
9. Continue to do this until all hearts have been used. 
10. Glue the last two hearts together to create a 3D heart 💕
